      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey i need some help with some savings math. if i start with $5000 in an account and add $200 every month, how much will i have after 30 years if i get a 7% annual return? can u show me how the math works?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Sure, let's break it down:\n\n1. Your initial investment: $5000\n2. Monthly savings contribution: $200\n3. Annual return rate: 7%\n4. Duration: 30 years (360 months)\n\nFirst, calculate the future value of the initial investment at 7% annual interest over 30 years:\n\nFuture Value = Principal * (1 + Interest Rate)^Years\nPrincipal = $5000\nInterest Rate = 7% = 0.07\nYears = 30\nFuture Value = $5000 * (1 + 0.07)^30 ≈ $38,697.84\n\nNext, calculate the future value of a series of monthly contributions:\n\nFuture Value of Annuity = Contribution * (((1 + r/n)^(nt) - 1) / (r/n))\nContribution = $200 per month\nInterest Rate = 7% = 0.07\nNumber of times compounded: n = 12 (monthly)\nNumber of years: 30\n\nFuture Value = $200 * (((1 + 0.07/12)^(12*30) - 1) / (0.07/12))\nFuture Value ≈ $868,435.62",
      "source": "target",
